Electronic Cigarettes Among Youth in the United States

Madison Stoms, Rebecca Silva, Robert Tumasian, and Charlotte Fowler

November 16, 2019

Motivation

E-cigarettes have become a growing public health concern. As of October 29, 2019, 1,888 cases of lung injury due to e-cigarette use, or vaping, have been reported to the CDC from 49 states (1). Medical officials have become increasingly interested in the development of lung disease among users; however, there is still little known about this topic. While e-cigarettes and vapes were initially intended for current smokers to reduce tobacco dependency, these products have been largely marketed to teenagers with no smoking history. The goal of this project is to better understand trends in e-cigarette use among youth in order to inform the development and implementation of preventive and therapeutic interventions.

Related Work

As e-cigarettes were linked to cases of lung injury, many began criticizing suppliers, particularly because of their marketing towards teenagers. Companies such as JUUL were accused of social media campaigns and fruity flavors to attract younger users. Many have studied this phenomenon through surveys to understand the young users and their interest in e-cigarettes. Vallone et al conducted a nationally representative survey of participants aged 15-21 in 2018, and found that younger age, white race, higher socioeconomic status and perception that e-cigs are less harmful than cigarettes all correlated with a higher chance of using e-cigarettes (2). Similarly, Willet et al conducted an online survey to detect that in 2017, one fourth of youth and young adults recognized a JUUL device, and identified a lack of awareness of the potential harms of the tobacco in electronic cigarettes (3). However, neither of these studies were able to analyze e-cigarette use across time.

Initial Questions

How has e-cigarette use among youth changed across time? Firstly, we wished to visualize and answer this question. While we know from outside sources that they have become more popular in across time, we hoped to demonstrate this curve and understand when and to what degree the change happened.

Next, we asked: What factors put an individual more at risk of e-cigarette use? To answer this question, we consider demographics such as age, sex, and race, as well as cigarette consumption, perception towards the harm of e-cigarettes, and ads viewed for e-cigarettes.

To differ from previous studies, we also wanted to consider the geographical dispersion of the epidemic, and attempts to reduce youth acccess to e-cigarettes. Therefore, we ask: How has legislation changed across time and space to address growing use of e-cigarettes in the United States?

Data

Our analysis was conducted using two data sources. The fist dataset is the National Youth Tobacco Use survey collected by the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (4). The raw data contains seperate surveys conducted in each year between 1999-2018. The surveys were given to 8-19 year olds across the country to address trends in tobacco use. To clean the data, we parsed each survey and identified questions pertaining to e-cigarette that were consistent among years. Since e-cigarette questions were not introduced until 2011, we restricted our analysis to years 2011-2018. Some questions of interest were not included in all years. To account for this, we assigned missing values to observation contained in the years in which the question was not addressed. The resulting dataset, ecig_data contains 160384 observations and 17 variables:

  • cig_days: How many cigarettes have you smoked in the past 30 days?
    levels: 0, 1-2, 3-5, 6-9, 10-19, 20-29, 30
  • try_ecigs: Have you ever tried electronic cigarettes?
    levels: yes, no
  • current_ecigs: Have you used electronic cigarettes in the last 30 days?
    levels: yes, no
  • quit_cig: Are you trying to quit cigarettes?
    levels: not a smoker, within the next 30 days, within the next 6 months, within 1 year, in over a year, no
  • heard_ecigs: Have you heard of electronic cigarettes?
    levels: yes, no years: 2012-2013
  • harm_ecigs: In your opinon, how harmful are electronic cigarettes compared to regular cigarettes?
    levels: less harmful, equally harmful, more harmful, never heard of e-cigarettes, unknown years: 2012-2018
  • age_first_ecig: What age were you when you used an electronic cigarette for the first time?
    levels: never, 8 or younger, 9-18 years: 2014-2018
  • reasons_ecigs: Are you using electronic cigarettes to quit smoking?
    levels: yes, no years: 2015-2018
  • ads_ecigs : When using the internet, how often do you see advertisements for electronic cigarettes?
  • weight : an assigned weight to balance demographic group representation
  • year
  • sex
  • race : levels: white, black, hispanic, asian, american indian / alaska native, native hawaiian / other pacific islander

Missingness varies over years and variables. In our analyses, we use only complete case.

The second source is the CDCs State Tobacco Activities Tracking and Evaluation System (5). The data contain information on electronic cigarette legislation across the U.S. from 2011 to 2018.
The resulting data set, legislation_data has 48960 observations and 5 variables including:

  • year
  • location_abbr : state abbreviation
  • location_desc : state name
  • effective_date : date on which the legislation was effective
  • geo_location

Lastly, we will briefly refer to the CDCs State Specific Patterns of E-Cigarette Use from 2016 (6). This data provides the prevalence of current adult e-cigarette users in each state. The data has 51 rows, for each state and the District of Columbia, and 4 variables, for state name, the total prevalence, male prevalence, and female prevalence.
